this is a time consuming and possibly fruitless exercise which most readers won't bother So what do you do if you have a new encryption scheme First of all find out if it's really Look through this FAQ for references and related Familiarize yourself with the literature and the introductory When you can appreciate how your cryptosystem fits into the world at large try to break it yourself You shouldn't waste the time of tens of thousands of readers asking a question which you could have easily answered on your If you really think your system is secure and you want to get some reassurance from experts you might try posting full details of your system including working code and a solid theoretical explanation to Keep in mind that the export of cryptography is regulated in some If you're lucky an expert might take some interest in what you You can encourage this by offering cash rewards for instance noted cryptographer Ralph Merkle is offering to anyone who can break Snefru but there are no If you don't have enough experience then most likely any experts who look at your system will be able to find a If this happens it's your responsibility to consider the flaw and learn from it rather than just add one more layer of complication and come back for another A different way to get your cryptosystem reviewed is to have the NSA look at A full discussion of this procedure is outside the scope of this Among professionals a common rule of thumb is that if you want to design a cryptosystem you have to have experience as a